function p = rtp (x)% RTP Real Trigonometric Polynomial %    P = RTP (X) ->	returns the RTP coefficients of vector X, which must be%    real. For matrices, the RTP operation is applied to each column. %%    For length N input vector X, the RTP is a length N vector P, with %    elements [ a(0) a(1) ... a(M1) b(1) ... b(M2) ]', where%  %        M1 = N/2   if N is even or (N-1)/2 if N is odd,%        M2 = N/2-1 if N is even or (N-1)/2 if N is odd,%%                          N%        a(0) = sqrt(1/N) sum x(n)%                         n=1%%                          N%        a(k) = sqrt(2/N) sum x(n) cos(2*pi*k*n/N),  1 <= k <= M1%                         n=0%%                           N%        b(k) = -sqrt(2/N) sum x(n) sin(2*pi*k*n/N),  1 <= k <= M2%                          n=0% %    The inverse RTP (computed by IRTP) is given by%                                          M1%        x(n) = sqrt(2/N)*(a(0)/sqrt(2) + sum a(k)* cos(2*pi*k*n/N) %                                         k=1%                  M2%               - sum b(k)*sin(2*pi*k*n/N))%                 k=1%%    Important property: norm(P) == norm(x)%%    See also IRTP, HR_SHIFT, HR_ALIGN, HR_INTERP.% Copyright (c) 2006-2009. Kevin C. McGill and others.% Part of EMGlab version 1.0.% This work is licensed under the Aladdin free public license.% For copying permissions see license.txt.% email: emglab@emglab.net	c = fft(x);	lx = size(x,1);	p = dft_to_rtp (c, lx);	p = p * sqrt(2/lx);